Little did they know that in the next 40 years, their company will outgrow Microsoft software products, including BASIC. While millions of children grew up using the BASIC interpreter now that BASIC is no more, we here at VisualBasic.net feel a bit unsettled. Come to think about it, we cannot recall the last time that old people used BASIC.
Here is a post, there was a post, and there were some posts before that. Now that everyone remembersSyntax Highlighter, it appears that those posts have migrated off the archive and into the deep internet. Do some googling, and you will get to them I am sure.
What happened? Do you know?
Do see more about the MS Open-Source History Project over at datamachinery.com, including Bill Gates' quote of the time.
In case you are unfamiliar with the MS Open-Source History Project, it includes the history of MS TechNet as a source code archive.
In 1975 Bill Gates and Paul Allen founded Microsoft. They were soaring high in their dot-com age. In their minds, every program was also running BASIC, and maybe even starting from a completely unlicensed version. They had no inkling about open source and Linux. Now of course the IE team would've instantly thought "How to break this innocent little BASIC thing?", as it was just put on the internet a few days back. But still the idea that a group of programmers who made sure BASIC can work, will eventually do the same for the whole world.
In 1991 Next Up from Microsoft was released. Microsoft can be once again recognized as we take closer look at the key features of NU. Could it be the beginnings of Microsoft's next ISP (InterSystems Platform)? If so, we would have been implementing NU even then. It's still a secret for now, since Processor currently does not introduce NU in any of its products.
